Notebook[{
Cell["Continuous functions on a closed interval", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"73c41771-15ce-462f-85f8-53e79d6cbab4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Continuous functions are NOT part of this library's real-number theory \
\[Dash] ",
 "in a typical real-analysis course they are the next chapter after the \
topology of ",
 "the line. But the point-set topology we already have (open / closed / \
compact / ",
 "connected) makes the classical theorems on a closed interval fall out \
cheaply. ",
 "Everything below is kernel-checked, 0-sorry, ",
 "and lives in the demo file ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"demos", "/", 
   RowBox[{"Continuous", ".", "wl"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0fd34162-2731-487a-827d-bf1618f53317"],
 ". Evaluate the ",
 "cells top to bottom (Shift+Enter)."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a68070f5-f9fe-4617-a774-ce725fb52a26"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"110f7555-ad8f-40ee-ae03-4164c875fc8e"],

Cell["\<\
Load the kernel + stdlib snapshot and the continuity development:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8ea61317-1cf6-497e-9d91-4e4a7dbc92e7"],

Cell["\<\
(* Load the kernel + stdlib snapshot, then the (demo) continuity theory. *)
root = ParentDirectory[NotebookDirectory[]];
Global`$HOLEncapsulationMode = \"Stable\";
Get[FileNameJoin[{root, \"bootstrap.mx\"}]];
$ContextPath = Join[
  Select[Contexts[], StringMatchQ[#, \"HOL`*\"] && ! StringContainsQ[#, \
\"Private`\"] &],
  $ContextPath];
Get[FileNameJoin[{root, \"demos\", \"Continuous.wl\"}]];
$ContextPath = Prepend[$ContextPath, \"HOL`Demos`Continuous`\"];\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"71fa3c9d-26e2-4063-bee5-81b57dbbabfb"],

Cell["1. Continuity, topologically", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8956ee24-04a1-4fff-b924-ef0a6961c33f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We use the topological definition: f is continuous when the preimage of \
every ",
 "open set is open. No epsilons, no limits \[Dash] just ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "isOpen"],ExpressionUUID->"b6b1175a-d84a-47cc-b1a6-e2408f5f3133"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "PREIMAGE"],ExpressionUUID->"96452962-97fc-4100-b95d-07682eeea337"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"055e01df-e65a-4cdd-bc18-cbdc374197d7"],

Cell["formatThm[continuousDefThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"38be7058-4f74-4ab8-bec9-61f2060ba246"],

Cell["2. The two image theorems", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"028337f7-4b08-4c65-9036-3e99506a3f86"],

Cell["\<\
The continuous image of a compact set is compact (pull an open cover of the \
image back through f, take a finite subcover, push it forward):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7cde14c7-e275-43f8-9849-2192ec9f671c"],

Cell["formatThm[continuousImageCompactThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"a1b97229-d044-46fb-94e0-b6d24243436f"],

Cell["\<\
The continuous image of a connected set is connected (a separation of the \
image pulls back to a separation of the domain):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"55156a6c-58bf-4f4c-bb6e-13b6d072cd19"],

Cell["formatThm[continuousImageConnectedThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"c2ad6e6d-20f7-416d-9fdb-7c9019686852"],

Cell["3. A closed interval is compact", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"cbaae170-47ca-4e9d-ae4e-415c68db6e2d"],

Cell["\<\
[a,b] is closed (Topology) and bounded (lo=a, hi=b), hence compact:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f2b9747b-b74f-450e-b281-b069a918219e"],

Cell["formatThm[closedIntervalCompactThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"4eae6cc4-5a9b-43af-ae04-560c98d368d3"],

Cell["4. Boundedness on [a,b]", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"4e2ffd02-19f9-4a8e-b3b1-141bab16006a"],

Cell["\<\
[a,b] is compact, so its continuous image is compact, hence closed and \
bounded \[Dash] in particular bounded. A continuous function on a closed \
interval is bounded:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"17783407-05ac-45e9-b887-d1a57b333b11"],

Cell["formatThm[continuousImageBoundedThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"22a69402-54e4-4eef-b4e0-197c918417fb"],

Cell["5. The intermediate value theorem", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"cbaaa07f-abe8-46be-b62c-441cb5d89a88"],

Cell["\<\
[a,b] is also connected, so its continuous image is connected, hence an \
interval. Since the image contains f(a) and f(b), it contains every value \
between them \[Dash] the function-form IVT, proved from pure topology with no \
continuous-function analysis:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"64a595d9-9064-4c76-8923-543311a94306"],

Cell["formatThm[continuousIVTThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"3d56b1a9-7ced-43ea-ab0f-5ac3d1440809"],

Cell["6. The extreme value theorem", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"dc688f00-2d44-41e7-86b6-27c1dc63c1bc"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The image of [a,b] is also compact, hence closed and bounded, so its \
supremum ",
 "is attained: there is a point where f reaches its maximum. The proof builds \
a ",
 "sequence approaching the supremum (each term within ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"n", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b19668dd-9602-425d-b785-cc2fd0689212"],
 " of it), uses that a closed set contains its sequential ",
 "limits, and reads the maximiser off the resulting image membership:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5d66db05-8a17-4589-9fbc-d97a1ed22543"],

Cell["formatThm[continuousEVTThm]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"07732197-9689-480b-826e-81e53c5033bc"],

Cell["A live check", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d2378d1a-da00-48e1-b034-e7be37307e47"],

Cell["\<\
Each statement above is a real theorem object; the kernel built it. For \
example, the EVT has no hypotheses beyond the ones shown, and is genuinely a \
theorem:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"97f25798-ba8a-4296-8db8-ed395a5151d3"],

Cell["{isThm[continuousEVTThm], hyp[continuousEVTThm]}", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"76c06fe3-f1d4-4acb-8102-8b9b26cce9ef"],

Cell["Next steps", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"eec2d803-db04-4154-aaa7-4821f70e62af"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "See ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"demos", "/", 
   RowBox[{"Continuous", ".", "wl"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "62909401-3c27-4c36-b777-dc1b2763c52b"],
 " for the proofs and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"docs", "/", 
   RowBox[{"USER_GUIDE", ".", "md"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "32408d06-4887-4f43-af65-3011986eabdd"],
 " for the API."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1952ecd9-4e3d-40f8-9eea-345b84cad6f4"]
},
WindowSize->{820, 720},
